        "username": "bfaccini"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-08 10:39:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "cf5ca78f5199156bd98a1e693cc63daae92d7216",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-11 03:42:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nPlease don't force cfs_hash to use atomic allocator, lustre can have very large hash table and can have hundreds of thousands cfs_hash instances.\nI think this bug should be fixed in a different way, first it is wrong to create hash table inside ldlm_flock_completion_ast()->ldlm_flock_blocking_link()->ldlm_init_flock_export(), I can't see which lock is protecting this assignment:\n \"exp->exp_flock_hash = cfs_hash_create(...)\"\nI think this assignment should be protected by a lock of obd_export, not by lock_res_and_lock(). \nmy hunch is, we should create cfs_hash() in a different place, e.g. ldlm_flock_completion_ast() before holding lock_res_and_lock() and calling ldlm_process_flock_lock()",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "6a693753b02ffafc1705b0070ac8caa2c59bf66d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 229,
        "name": "Bruno Faccini",
        "email": "bfaccini@nvidia.com",
        "username": "bfaccini"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-11 08:50:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nLiang, thank's for your feedback! That's why I requested your review because I thought you have the necessary experience to decide atomic allocation is a good/bad idea !!!! And it is also why I proposed a 2nd way to fix in Change #6843 for  same LU-3504, where I do the allocation from ldlm_lock_enqueue(). Feel free to comment/review in #6843 too !!",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "5773a93a263a90773d3d9b5c18820c756b701464",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-15 15:18:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nLiang, I agree we should move cfs_hash_create() out from under the spin lock. That's unanimous I think, but that solves only half of the current issue with ldlm_flock_blocking_link()\n\nWithout changing the hashing allocation to be atomic, we still run the risk of sleeping when calling cfs_hash_add(). We *cannot* sleep unless we can refactor the code to drop the spin lock.\n\nPerhaps we need to introduce a way to force the allocations to be atomic using a more granular approach. That way it would only affect the necessary allocation, making them atomic, but not any other calls (e.g. using a parameter or hash initialization flag).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "8850fb1a16315740d54168b63c30e424785a7e5b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-16 03:00:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: No score\n\ncfs_hash_add() is atomic by default, it will schedule a \"workitem\" to rehash if necessary (workitem is briefly a different thread).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "cf500d5a120f64515ae3f7f3cd5dfc2b740aa31c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-16 16:55:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nAhh, I see now. It will return from cfs_hash_add and do the rehash in another thread. Since that's the case, I don't see why this patch is needed?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "4b81a7ed32bf676f7f20ff49f45cebedaa206901",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-18 01:40:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nthis issue is because cfs_hash_create is called with hold of spinlock, not because cfs_hash_add which is safe to call with lock",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "f03564d3cff749adf60c52891a590b5a67dc0992",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
